    options: [
      { text: "Selenium and iodine are both required for normal thyroid function; combined deficiency worsens hypothyroidism", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Selenium-containing iodothyronine deiodinases convert T4 (thyroxine) to the active T3 (triiodothyronine); selenium deficiency impairs this conversion. In iodine-deficient populations, concurrent selenium deficiency further disrupts thyroid hormone homeostasis, worsening the severity of hypothyroidism and goiter — a clinically important interaction in developing countries." },
      { text: "Selenium and iron compete for the same intestinal transporters", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Selenium and iron do not share the same intestinal transporters; iron absorption uses DMT1 and ferroportin, while selenium is absorbed as selenate/selenite via different pathways. The clinically relevant selenium interaction is with iodine (thyroid function), not iron absorption competition." },
      { text: "Selenium and calcium have antagonistic effects on bone density", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "There is no established clinically relevant antagonistic relationship between selenium and calcium affecting bone density; bone mineralization depends primarily on calcium, phosphorus, vitamin D, and vitamin K. The Kashin-Beck disease associated with selenium deficiency affects cartilage and growth plates, not classic bone density through a calcium-selenium interaction." },
      { text: "Selenium and vitamin C have synergistic antioxidant effects in clinical outcomes", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While selenium (via GPx) and vitamin C are both antioxidants, there is no clinically proven synergistic effect on disease outcomes in humans; antioxidant supplementation trials have generally been disappointing. The most evidence-based selenium interaction is with iodine in thyroid metabolism, not with vitamin C in clinical outcomes." }
    ],
