  {
    question: "A 6-month-old infant is exposed to measles. She is too young for MMR vaccination. What is the appropriate post-exposure prophylaxis?",
    bloomLevel: "Application",
    competencyCode: "PE11.2",
    competencyText: "Apply post-exposure prophylaxis for measles in infants",
    options: [
      { text: "Intramuscular immunoglobulin within 6 days of exposure", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "For infants too young for MMR vaccine (<6 months), or immunocompromised individuals, intramuscular immunoglobulin given within 6 days of exposure provides passive antibody protection. The dose is 0.5 mL/kg IM. This is the recommended post-exposure prophylaxis per CDC guidelines for those who cannot receive live vaccine." },
      { text: "Oral acyclovir for 5 days", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Acyclovir is an antiviral effective against herpesviruses (HSV, VZV) and has no activity against measles virus, which is a paramyxovirus. There is no licensed antiviral for measles post-exposure prophylaxis; passive immunization with immunoglobulin is the only evidence-based intervention for high-risk exposed individuals." },
      { text: "MMR vaccine even in infants under 6 months as emergency measure", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "MMR is not recommended before 6 months of age because maternal antibodies interfere with vaccine immunogenicity, making it ineffective. Additionally, the infant immune system may not mount adequate response. For infants <6 months exposed to measles, intramuscular immunoglobulin is the appropriate intervention." },
      { text: "No prophylaxis as maternal antibodies are protective", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Maternal antibodies against measles wane by 4-6 months of age, and in communities with widespread MMR vaccination, maternal antibody titers may be lower than in naturally infected mothers. A 6-month-old cannot be assumed to have adequate passive protection and should receive immunoglobulin following documented exposure." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "24814559", title: "Vaccines are not associated with autism: an evidence-based meta-analysis of case-control and cohort studies.", publicationType: "Meta-Analysis" }
  },
  {
    question: "Vitamin A supplementation is recommended by WHO for all children with measles in developing countries. What is the rationale?",
    bloomLevel: "Understanding",
    competencyCode: "PE11.1",
    competencyText: "Understand role of vitamin A in measles management",
    options: [
      { text: "Vitamin A deficiency worsens measles severity; supplementation reduces mortality, pneumonia, and blindness", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Vitamin A is critical for maintaining mucosal integrity and immune function. In developing countries where deficiency is prevalent, measles depletes vitamin A stores, worsening complications including pneumonia, diarrhea, and corneal ulceration leading to blindness. WHO-recommended high-dose vitamin A supplementation (200,000 IU for 2 days) reduces measles mortality by up to 50%." },
      { text: "Vitamin A has direct antiviral activity against measles virus", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Vitamin A does not have direct antiviral activity against measles virus; it does not inhibit viral replication. Its benefit is immunomodulatory—restoring immune function in deficient patients and maintaining mucosal barriers. The mechanism is correction of deficiency-related immune impairment, not direct antiviral action." },
      { text: "Vitamin A reverses the immune amnesia caused by measles", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Vitamin A supplementation does not reverse measles-induced immune amnesia (depletion of memory lymphocytes). Immune amnesia results from direct viral destruction of memory B and T cells and cannot be corrected by vitamins. Vitamin A reduces acute complication severity and mortality but does not restore previously acquired immunological memory." },
      { text: "Vitamin A supplementation is standard for all febrile illnesses in children, not specific to measles", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "High-dose vitamin A supplementation is specifically recommended by WHO for measles in children in developing countries or those with vitamin A deficiency, malnutrition, or immunodeficiency. It is not a routine treatment for all febrile illnesses. This specific recommendation is based on measles-specific depletion of vitamin A stores." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "24814559", title: "Vaccines are not associated with autism: an evidence-based meta-analysis of case-control and cohort studies.", publicationType: "Meta-Analysis" }
  },
  {
    question: "Which measles complication accounts for the majority of measles-related deaths in developing countries?",
    bloomLevel: "Analysis",
    competencyCode: "PE11.1",
    competencyText: "Analyze leading cause of measles mortality",
    options: [
      { text: "Pneumonia (measles pneumonitis or secondary bacterial pneumonia)", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Pneumonia accounts for approximately 60% of measles deaths, occurring either as giant-cell pneumonitis from direct measles virus infection of the lungs or secondary bacterial superinfection (S. aureus, S. pneumoniae, H. influenzae). Measles-related immune suppression predisposes to bacterial pneumonia; this is the leading cause of measles mortality in developing countries." },
      { text: "Encephalitis from direct CNS invasion", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Measles encephalitis is a serious complication occurring in approximately 1 in 1,000 cases and carries 15% mortality, but it is far less common than pneumonia. While encephalitis is a significant cause of measles-related death and disability, pneumonia occurs more frequently and accounts for the majority of measles mortality globally." },
      { text: "Severe gastroenteritis from enteric measles", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Diarrhea and gastroenteritis do occur in measles and contribute to mortality in malnourished children, but they are not the leading cause of measles death. Pneumonia remains the dominant killer. The misconception likely arises because measles has enteric complications, but these are secondary to the respiratory disease burden." },
      { text: "SSPE as long-term complication", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "SSPE, while universally fatal, occurs in only 1 in 10,000-100,000 measles cases and develops 7-10 years after acute infection. It is not a significant contributor to overall measles mortality statistics. The acute complications, primarily pneumonia, account for the vast majority of measles-related deaths." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "24814559", title: "Vaccines are not associated with autism: an evidence-based meta-analysis of case-control and cohort studies.", publicationType: "Meta-Analysis" }
  },
  {
    question: "A parent refuses MMR for their child citing a debunked 1998 Wakefield paper. What is the most effective evidence-based communication strategy?",
    bloomLevel: "Evaluation",
    competencyCode: "CM2.1",
    competencyText: "Evaluate vaccine hesitancy communication strategies",
    options: [
      { text: "Motivational interviewing - explore concerns non-judgmentally, present individualized benefit-risk data, avoid confrontation", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Motivational interviewing (MI) is the evidence-based approach for vaccine hesitancy, emphasizing non-judgmental exploration of parental concerns, reflective listening, and collaborative decision-making. Studies show that confrontational approaches backfire and entrench anti-vaccine beliefs. MI respects parental autonomy while gently correcting misinformation with tailored risk-benefit information." },
      { text: "Present statistics alone without addressing emotional concerns", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Research consistently shows that providing statistics and facts alone is insufficient to change vaccine-hesitant parents' minds and can even backfire. Vaccine hesitancy is emotionally driven and rooted in trust issues; addressing the emotional and relational dimensions through motivational interviewing is more effective than data-only approaches." },
      { text: "State that Wakefield was fraudulent and the parent is wrong", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Directly telling a parent they are wrong or that a figure they trust was fraudulent triggers psychological reactance, entrenching their beliefs. This is a common mistake by well-meaning clinicians. The evidence shows that non-confrontational motivational interviewing is far more effective than argumentation in shifting vaccine-hesitant parents toward acceptance." },
      { text: "Mandate vaccination without engaging with parental concerns", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While vaccine mandates exist in some jurisdictions as public health policy, dismissing parental concerns without engagement damages the therapeutic relationship and reduces future healthcare engagement. The clinical standard is empathetic communication using motivational interviewing principles before any coercive approach is considered." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "24814559", title: "Vaccines are not associated with autism: an evidence-based meta-analysis of case-control and cohort studies.", publicationType: "Meta-Analysis" }
  }
