      { text: "Annual mammography starting at age 50", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "The previous 2016 USPSTF recommendation was biennial mammography starting at age 50, with age 40-49 screening being an individual decision. The 2024 update lowered the starting age to 40. Some other organizations (ACR, SBI) recommend annual mammography starting at 40, but the current USPSTF recommendation is biennial from age 40." },
      { text: "MRI breast screening annually from age 40", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Annual breast MRI is recommended only for high-risk women—those with BRCA1/2 mutations, lifetime risk >20%, or prior chest radiation—not average-risk women. MRI has higher sensitivity but lower specificity than mammography, leading to more false positives and unnecessary biopsies when used in average-risk populations." },
      { text: "No screening until age 50 for average-risk women", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "This reflects outdated or overly conservative interpretation. The 2024 USPSTF now explicitly recommends biennial mammography beginning at age 40 for average-risk women, recognizing that screening in the 40s reduces breast cancer mortality. Delaying until age 50 would miss cancers in women in their 40s, a period of significant breast cancer incidence." }
