  {
    question: "A patient with renal failure develops amantadine-induced psychosis with visual hallucinations. After dialysis and drug discontinuation, symptoms persist for 5 days. What explains this?",
    bloomLevel: "Understanding",
    competencyCode: "TX1.2",
    competencyText: "Understand persistence of amantadine toxicity after treatment",
    options: [
      { text: "High volume of distribution means amantadine redistributes from tissues back to circulation despite dialysis, requiring multiple sessions", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Amantadine has a large volume of distribution (approximately 5-10 L/kg) because it extensively accumulates in tissues. After each dialysis session removes drug from plasma, tissue stores redistribute amantadine back into the circulation (rebound effect), requiring repeated dialysis sessions to achieve lasting detoxification. This pharmacokinetic property explains symptom persistence despite apparent dialysis adequacy." },
      { text: "Dialysis is ineffective for amantadine removal so persistence is expected", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Dialysis IS effective at removing amantadine from plasma (amantadine is dialyzable due to low protein binding), but the persistent redistribution from tissue stores creates a rebound effect requiring multiple sessions. The distinction between dialysis-effective but redistribution-limited (amantadine) versus dialysis-ineffective (some large protein-bound drugs) is clinically important for treatment planning." },
      { text: "Permanent dopaminergic receptor damage from amantadine toxicity", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Amantadine toxicity is pharmacological (receptor overstimulation/blockade) rather than structural neurotoxicity. The symptoms resolve as plasma levels fall; permanent receptor damage does not occur with amantadine at clinically encountered toxic doses. Persistence reflects ongoing drug presence (redistribution), not receptor injury. This distinction is important for prognosis and patient counseling." },
      { text: "Co-existing viral encephalitis from the influenza infection", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Influenza encephalitis would not resolve predictably with amantadine clearance and would not respond to dialysis. The temporal correlation between drug accumulation (unrecognized AKI on amantadine) and symptom onset, combined with symptom improvement tracking drug removal, clearly establishes a pharmacological rather than infectious etiology for the encephalopathy." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "19328395", title: "Obstructive acute renal failure related to amantadine intoxication.", publicationType: "Journal Article" }
  }
