      { text: "Vitiligo with peripheral neuropathy", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Vitiligo causes hypopigmentation but the lesions retain sensation and nerve thickening does not occur; a skin slit smear would be AFB-negative, distinguishing it immediately from leprosy." },
      { text: "Paucibacillary tuberculosis with skin manifestations", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "M. tuberculosis and M. leprae are both AFB, but skin TB (lupus vulgaris) does not cause peripheral nerve thickening or a positive skin slit smear; leprosy specifically targets Schwann cells, producing a neuritic pattern absent in TB." },
      { text: "Sarcoidosis with peripheral neuropathy and skin lesions", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Sarcoidosis produces non-caseating granulomas and can affect skin and nerves but is not AFB-positive; a skin slit smear would show no organisms, and the tropical exposure history with nerve thickening strongly favors an infectious mycobacterial etiology." }
