      { text: "Colchicine is safe throughout pregnancy and should be continued; discontinuation increases attack frequency and amyloidosis risk", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Multiple large cohort studies and the EUROFEVER registry demonstrate no increased fetal malformation rates with colchicine at therapeutic doses throughout pregnancy; uncontrolled FMF attacks during pregnancy increase preterm birth risk and maintain chronic inflammation driving amyloid A accumulation; current international FMF guidelines recommend continuing colchicine throughout pregnancy and lactation." },
      { text: "Colchicine is teratogenic and must be stopped at conception", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Early animal study concerns about colchicine teratogenicity have not been confirmed in decades of human pregnancy data; this outdated warning has been definitively superseded by modern observational cohort data showing equivalent malformation rates in colchicine-exposed versus unexposed pregnancies; current guidelines explicitly recommend continuation." },
      { text: "Switch to NSAIDs for acute attacks during pregnancy instead of colchicine", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "NSAIDs are relatively contraindicated in the third trimester due to premature ductus arteriosus constriction and oligohydramnios risk; using colchicine as continuous prophylaxis to prevent attacks is the standard approach; episodic NSAID treatment for breakthrough attacks is less effective and carries gestational risks." },
      { text: "Colchicine can be used only in the third trimester", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Colchicine should be maintained throughout all trimesters; the first trimester is the critical period for organogenesis where any potential teratogen is most dangerous, and colchicine has been shown safe in this period; restricting use to the third trimester would leave the most vulnerable period of pregnancy unprotected from FMF attacks." }
