      { text: "Any detectable lead level above zero requires chelation", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "No safe blood lead level exists for children, but chelation carries real risks (toxicity, redistribution) and is only justified at levels where clinical benefit clearly outweighs harm (typically 45 mcg/dL); low-level exposures require source removal, nutrition optimization, and close monitoring rather than chelation therapy." },
      { text: "Chelation only indicated above 70 mcg/dL with encephalopathy", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Chelation is appropriate at 45 mcg/dL or above in children regardless of symptoms; waiting for encephalopathy (typically presenting above 70-100 mcg/dL) significantly delays treatment and increases permanent neurological damage; the 45 mcg/dL threshold is the intervention point, with encephalopathy requiring the more aggressive BAL+EDTA combination." },
      { text: "Asymptomatic children with any BLL do not require chelation", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Asymptomatic children with BLL at or above 45 mcg/dL require chelation; cognitive and neurological effects from lead occur subclinically at much lower levels; the absence of acute symptoms does not negate the need for chelation once the threshold BLL is reached; asymptomatic severe lead toxicity is a medical emergency." }
