      { text: "Iron deposition in hepatocytes causing mitochondrial dysfunction, necrosis, and potentially fulminant hepatic failure", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Absorbed iron accumulates in hepatocytes where excess ferrous iron enters mitochondria and generates hydroxyl radicals via the Fenton reaction; mitochondrial electron chain dysfunction impairs ATP synthesis and triggers hepatocyte necrosis with AST/ALT elevation; severe cases progress to fulminant hepatic failure with coagulopathy and encephalopathy." },
      { text: "Hemolysis releasing heme iron causing bilirubinemia", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Hemolysis with indirect hyperbilirubinemia occurs in hemolytic anemias; Stage 4 iron hepatotoxicity is direct hepatocellular necrosis from mitochondrial oxidative damage producing elevated ALT/AST; while mild hemolysis can occur in iron toxicity, the predominant hepatic injury mechanism is direct oxidative hepatocellular necrosis." },
      { text: "Intrahepatic cholestasis from iron bile precipitates", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Iron does not precipitate in bile ducts; cholestatic liver disease presents with elevated alkaline phosphatase, GGT, and direct bilirubin; iron toxicity causes hepatocellular necrosis (elevated ALT/AST) from mitochondrial oxidative damage, not obstructive cholestatic disease." },
      { text: "Immune-mediated hepatitis triggered by iron-protein adducts", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Immune-mediated drug-induced liver injury involves hapten-protein adduct formation triggering adaptive immune responses with lymphocytic infiltration; iron toxicity causes direct dose-dependent hepatocellular necrosis through Fenton reaction chemistry, not immune-mediated drug hypersensitivity; the injury is predictable and dose-proportional, unlike idiosyncratic immune-mediated DILI." }
