      { text: "Brain abscess, encephalomyelitis, or flaccid paraparesis (neurological melioidosis is second most common after pulmonary)", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Neurological melioidosis is the second most common severe manifestation after pulmonary disease; B. pseudomallei disseminates hematogenously to the CNS causing brain abscesses, brainstem encephalomyelitis, or spinal cord myelitis with characteristic flaccid limb weakness; meropenem rather than ceftazidime is preferred for neurological melioidosis due to superior CNS penetration." },
      { text: "Bacterial meningitis with cloudy CSF", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Pyogenic bacterial meningitis with cloudy CSF and neutrophilic pleocytosis is uncommon in melioidosis; neurological melioidosis more typically presents as brain abscesses or granulomatous encephalomyelitis with lymphocytic CSF changes or normal CSF; the meningitis pattern is more characteristic of Neisseria meningitidis or Streptococcus pneumoniae." },
      { text: "Cerebral vasculitis causing stroke", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Cerebral vasculitis causing ischemic stroke is not the established mechanism of neurological melioidosis; B. pseudomallei causes direct parenchymal infection forming abscesses and inflammatory myelitis rather than inflammatory vasculopathy; stroke from melioidosis is uncommon compared to the characteristic abscess and myelitis presentations." },
      { text: "Peripheral neuropathy from B. pseudomallei neurotoxin", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "B. pseudomallei does not produce an established peripheral neurotoxin; the neurological tropism is for CNS parenchymal infection through hematogenous dissemination; the flaccid paraparesis seen in neurological melioidosis results from spinal cord myelitis (lower motor neuron pattern) from CNS invasion, not from a neurotoxic mechanism affecting peripheral nerves." }
