      { text: "Thalassemia - impaired neutrophil and macrophage function; hazard ratio similar to or exceeding that of diabetes in Thailand", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Thai epidemiological data demonstrates that thalassemia (particularly hemoglobin E/thalassemia) confers melioidosis risk comparable to or exceeding diabetes in endemic regions; iron overload from ineffective erythropoiesis impairs neutrophil and macrophage function, and iron may promote bacterial growth; geographic co-endemicity of thalassemia and B. pseudomallei makes this an important clinical association." },
      { text: "Cirrhosis from alcohol use", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Cirrhosis increases susceptibility to gram-negative infections through complement deficiency and macrophage dysfunction; it is a recognized melioidosis risk factor; however, the hazard ratio for cirrhosis is generally lower than for diabetes or thalassemia in most melioidosis case series from endemic regions." },
      { text: "HIV with CD4 count below 200", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "HIV does increase susceptibility to opportunistic infections; however, melioidosis is not characteristically associated with HIV in the same epidemiological strength as with diabetes and thalassemia; HIV-associated melioidosis is documented but is not the dominant risk factor identified in Southeast Asian and Australian epidemiological studies." },
      { text: "Systemic lupus erythematosus on immunosuppression", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "SLE on immunosuppression creates general infection risk; however, in melioidosis epidemiology SLE is not identified as a major independent risk factor; the specific combination of hyperglycemia-mediated innate immune dysfunction in diabetes and iron overload in thalassemia creates unique B. pseudomallei vulnerability not replicated by generalized immunosuppression." }
