      { text: "Generalized absence seizures", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Absence seizures cause brief loss of awareness with staring, superficially similar to the impaired consciousness in abdominal epilepsy. However, absence seizures originate from generalized spike-wave discharges and do not produce focal abdominal visceral aura." },
      { text: "Myoclonic seizures with autonomic features", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Some clinicians confuse abdominal sensations with autonomic features of myoclonic seizures. However, myoclonic seizures involve brief muscle jerks from cortical hyperexcitability; abdominal epilepsy involves visceral aura from focal temporal-insular ictal activity without prominent motor jerks." },
      { text: "Simple partial seizures without consciousness impairment", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Simple partial (focal aware) seizures preserve full consciousness throughout. Abdominal epilepsy typically involves impaired awareness because temporal lobe ictal activity spreads beyond the insular visceral cortex to involve limbic structures, classifying them as focal impaired awareness seizures." }
