      { text: "Danazol as first-line hormonal treatment", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Danazol (a synthetic androgen) is effective for endometriosis pain but is now a third-line option due to significant androgenic side effects (hirsutism, acne, voice changes, weight gain). Modern guidelines reserve it for refractory cases after COCs, progestins, and GnRH agonists have been tried." },
      { text: "GnRH agonist as first-line therapy for all endometriosis stages", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "GnRH agonists (leuprolide, nafarelin) are highly effective but are second-line due to significant bone loss with prolonged use (requiring add-back estrogen), cost, and menopausal side effects. They are reserved for patients who fail first-line hormonal therapy or require maximal preoperative suppression." },
      { text: "NSAIDs alone are adequate for stage I-II endometriosis", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "NSAIDs effectively manage dysmenorrhea but do not suppress endometrial implants or slow disease progression. For endometriosis management beyond simple pain relief, hormonal suppression with COCs or progestins is required, making NSAIDs insufficient as monotherapy." }
