      { text: "Constant pleuritic pain unrelated to menstrual cycle", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Constant pleuritic pain unrelated to the menstrual cycle suggests pleuritis, pneumonia, or malignancy rather than thoracic endometriosis. The hallmark of thoracic endometriosis is its cyclical catamenial pattern, timed with the onset or peak of menstruation." },
      { text: "Right-sided pleural effusion developing progressively", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Catamenial hemothorax does occur with thoracic endometriosis, usually on the right side due to diaphragmatic pores. However, it is episodic and menstrual-cycle dependent, not progressive. A progressively enlarging pleural effusion suggests malignancy or cardiac/hepatic causes." },
      { text: "Hemoptysis from intrabronchial endometriosis causing hemoptysis at any time", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "True intrabronchial endometriosis is extremely rare. Thoracic endometriosis more commonly involves the pleura and diaphragm. Critically, symptoms are catamenial (tied to menstruation), not occurring randomly at any time as would be expected from intrabronchial lesions." }
