    competencyText: "Apply diagnostic testing for leptospirosis",
    options: [
      { text: "MAT (microscopic agglutination test) for acute and convalescent titers (4-fold rise diagnostic); PCR for early acute phase; culture takes weeks", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "MAT (microscopic agglutination test) is the reference standard serological test for leptospirosis, detecting serovar-specific agglutinating antibodies. A 4-fold titer rise between acute and convalescent samples (2-3 weeks apart) is diagnostic. PCR from blood or urine is more sensitive in the first 5-7 days before antibody response develops." },
      { text: "Blood culture on standard media - Leptospira grows rapidly on blood agar", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Leptospira requires specialized media (EMJH semi-solid medium) at 28-30°C and takes 4-6 weeks to grow—far too slow for acute clinical decision-making. Standard blood culture media and incubation conditions are insufficient for Leptospira growth." },
      { text: "ELISA for IgM anti-leptospira antibodies is both sensitive and specific in the first week", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "IgM ELISA is used in endemic settings for point-of-care testing but has limited specificity in early disease and cross-reacts with other spirochetal and non-spirochetal infections. MAT remains the reference standard. ELISA IgM sensitivity in the first week of illness is also limited as antibody responses take several days to develop." },
      { text: "Weil-Felix reaction - a cross-reactive test diagnostic for leptospirosis", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "The Weil-Felix test uses Proteus OX antigens to detect rickettsial infections (not leptospirosis) through cross-reactive agglutination. It has poor sensitivity and specificity even for rickettsial diseases and has no role in leptospirosis diagnosis. Confusion may arise because both Weil disease (leptospirosis) and Weil-Felix test exist." }
    ],
