      { text: "Rice field workers, sewage workers, veterinarians, farmers, and military personnel in flood-prone areas", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Leptospirosis is transmitted through contact of skin or mucous membranes with water or soil contaminated by urine from infected animals (rats, cattle, pigs, dogs). Occupational groups with regular exposure to such environments carry highest risk: rice farmers, sewage/slaughterhouse workers, veterinarians, and military personnel conducting field exercises." },
      { text: "Healthcare workers from nosocomial transmission", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Person-to-person transmission of leptospirosis is extremely rare—healthcare workers are not at significantly elevated occupational risk from patient contact. Transmission requires contact with animal urine or contaminated water/soil; hospital precautions beyond standard precautions are not required." },
      { text: "Miners from soil dust inhalation", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Leptospirosis is not transmitted via inhalation of soil dust. Transmission requires direct skin or mucous membrane contact with infected animal urine or contaminated water (particularly through cuts, abrasions, or prolonged skin immersion). Dust inhalation is the transmission route for Coccidioides and Histoplasma, not Leptospira." },
      { text: "Urban office workers from rat-contaminated water supplies", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While rodents are the primary urban reservoir, indirect exposure through drinking water is not a significant transmission route in developed settings with treated water supplies. Urban leptospirosis outbreaks occur after flooding events creating rat-urine-contaminated flood water contact, not from routine tap water consumption." }
