      { text: "Peritoneal dialysis preferred over hemodialysis in tropical resource-limited settings (avoid vascular access complications)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Peritoneal dialysis is an option in resource-limited settings for leptospiral AKI and has been used successfully in endemic areas. However, with K 6.5 and anuria, urgent dialysis is needed and hemodialysis provides faster correction. The preferred modality depends on resource availability, but the urgency of intervention takes priority." },
      { text: "Volume replacement alone - leptospiral AKI always recovers without dialysis", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "While leptospiral AKI has a generally favorable recovery potential, life-threatening electrolyte abnormalities (K 6.5 with cardiac arrhythmia risk) and anuria cannot wait for spontaneous recovery. Volume replacement cannot correct established ATN with oliguria and dangerous hyperkalemia." },
      { text: "Hold all fluid given leptospirosis is a fluid-overload disease", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Leptospirosis with AKI requires careful fluid management, not fluid restriction. The AKI from direct tubular toxicity benefits from adequate volume to maintain renal perfusion, avoiding worsening prerenal component. Fluid restriction in the absence of frank pulmonary edema or severe heart failure would worsen tubular ischemia." }
