      { text: "Coccidioidomycosis - rounded spherules with endospores in tissue", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Coccidioides immitis/posadasii produces unique spherules (large round structures 20-200 microns) filled with endospores at 37°C in tissue, not budding yeast. Coccidioidomycosis is endemic to the Southwestern US, not the Mississippi Valley. The morphological distinction in tissue is definitive." },
      { text: "Histoplasmosis - small intracellular yeast in macrophages", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Histoplasma capsulatum produces small (2-4 micron) intracellular yeast within macrophages, easily mistaken for Leishmania. Histoplasmosis overlaps geographically with blastomycosis in the Ohio/Mississippi River valleys, but the morphological distinction in tissue (broad-based budding yeast vs. small intracellular yeast) is definitive." },
      { text: "Paracoccidioidomycosis - multiple buds (pilot wheel) appearance", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Paracoccidioides brasiliensis produces the pathognomonic pilot wheel appearance (large yeast with multiple peripheral buds) and is endemic to Latin America, not North America. The broad-based single bud of Blastomyces is distinct from the multiple buds of Paracoccidioides." }
