      { text: "Only immunocompromised patients (HIV, transplant)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "While immunocompromised patients have higher risk of severe sporotrichosis, pulmonary sporotrichosis specifically clusters in patients with underlying structural lung disease (COPD) and alcohol use, not just HIV or transplant immunosuppression. The local lung defense impairment from COPD is the key predisposing factor." },
      { text: "Rural workers exposed to sphagnum moss only", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Sphagnum moss is a classical environment associated with sporotrichosis transmission (the classic case being rosebush or sphagnum moss-associated skin inoculation). However, pulmonary sporotrichosis requires inhalation of conidia and particularly affects those with underlying COPD, not just environmental exposure." },
      { text: "Children under 5 from direct inhalation of soil fungus", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Children under 5 rarely develop pulmonary sporotrichosis. Primary pulmonary sporotrichosis predominantly affects adults with COPD and alcohol use. Most childhood sporotrichosis involves the lymphocutaneous form from skin inoculation, not inhalation-acquired pulmonary disease." }
