      { text: "ACE has low sensitivity (60%) and specificity for sarcoidosis; elevated in Gaucher disease, miliary TB, hyperthyroidism; not suitable as sole diagnostic test", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Serum ACE sensitivity for sarcoidosis is approximately 60% and specificity is insufficient for diagnosis (elevated in miliary TB, Gaucher disease, hyperthyroidism, liver disease, sarcoidosis). ACE is useful for monitoring disease activity in known sarcoidosis but cannot replace tissue diagnosis. Importantly, ACE may be normal in up to 40% of cases." },
      { text: "ACE level above 2x normal is diagnostic without biopsy", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "No specific ACE threshold is diagnostic for sarcoidosis without histological confirmation (except for Lofgren syndrome where biopsy is optional). Even markedly elevated ACE does not exclude TB, Gaucher, or other granulomatous conditions. Biopsy demonstrating non-caseating granulomas is required for definitive diagnosis." },
      { text: "Normal ACE level excludes sarcoidosis with high negative predictive value", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Normal ACE does not exclude sarcoidosis—up to 40% of cases have normal ACE levels, particularly in acute sarcoidosis (Lofgren syndrome) and localized disease. ACE sensitivity of approximately 60% means a normal result provides insufficient negative predictive value to rule out sarcoidosis." },
      { text: "ACE level directly correlates with disease activity and guides treatment withdrawal", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While ACE may decline with effective corticosteroid treatment, ACE levels have poor correlation with disease activity and do not reliably guide treatment withdrawal decisions. Clinical symptoms, pulmonary function testing, CT findings, and organ-specific markers are more reliable for monitoring sarcoidosis activity than ACE alone." }
