      { text: "Oral corticosteroids (suppress granulomatous 1-alpha-hydroxylase production, reducing calcitriol), IV hydration, and avoid sunlight/vitamin D supplementation", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Corticosteroids are the specific treatment for sarcoid hypercalcemia, directly suppressing macrophage 1-alpha-hydroxylase expression and reducing calcitriol production. Hydration corrects dehydration and promotes calciuresis. Avoiding sunlight and vitamin D supplements (which would provide substrate for granulomatous calcitriol production) is essential." },
      { text: "IV bisphosphonates as for malignant hypercalcemia", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Bisphosphonates inhibit osteoclast-mediated bone resorption and are the first-line for hypercalcemia of malignancy (osteolytic or PTHrP-mediated). In sarcoidosis, hypercalcemia is primarily from excess calcitriol-mediated gut absorption, not bone resorption—bisphosphonates address the wrong mechanism and are not the primary treatment." },
      { text: "Cinacalcet (calcimimetic) for sarcoid-related hypercalcemia", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Cinacalcet activates the calcium-sensing receptor on parathyroid cells to suppress PTH secretion—specifically treating primary hyperparathyroidism and uremic secondary hyperparathyroidism. In sarcoidosis, PTH is already suppressed by high calcitriol; cinacalcet would have no therapeutic target and is inappropriate." },
      { text: "Restrict dietary calcium as primary treatment", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Dietary calcium restriction alone is insufficient for sarcoid hypercalcemia. While modest calcium restriction is reasonable, the primary mechanism (excess calcitriol driving increased intestinal calcium absorption and bone resorption) requires corticosteroids to suppress the underlying granulomatous calcitriol production." }
