  {
    question: "A 25-year-old woman with sarcoidosis plans pregnancy. Which sarcoidosis complication specifically worsens during pregnancy?",
    bloomLevel: "Evaluation",
    competencyCode: "IM10.4",
    competencyText: "Evaluate sarcoidosis management in pregnancy",
    options: [
      { text: "Pulmonary sarcoidosis often improves during pregnancy (immune tolerance shift) but hypercalcemia can worsen due to increased 1-alpha-hydroxylase in placenta", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Pregnancy induces a shift toward Th2 immunity and immunological tolerance, which often suppresses granulomatous Th1 inflammation—explaining why pulmonary sarcoidosis frequently improves during pregnancy. However, the placenta expresses its own 1-alpha-hydroxylase, adding to calcitriol production and worsening hypercalcemia in susceptible patients." },
      { text: "Sarcoidosis invariably flares severely in all pregnant patients", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Sarcoidosis does not invariably worsen during pregnancy—in fact, the Th2 immunological shift of pregnancy often leads to improvement in granulomatous inflammation. Post-partum flares are more common than pregnancy-associated worsening. The exception is hypercalcemia, which may worsen due to placental calcitriol production." },
      { text: "Cardiac sarcoidosis is the only manifestation affected by pregnancy", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Multiple sarcoidosis manifestations can change during pregnancy. Pulmonary and cutaneous manifestations may improve due to Th2 immune shift. Hypercalcemia can worsen due to placental 1-alpha-hydroxylase. Cardiac sarcoidosis monitoring is important but is not the only manifestation affected by pregnancy." },
      { text: "Corticosteroids must be discontinued during pregnancy due to teratogenicity", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Corticosteroids (prednisolone in particular) are considered relatively safe in pregnancy and are often used for inflammatory and autoimmune conditions during gestation. They are not contraindicated for active sarcoidosis in pregnancy. The small increased risk of cleft palate with first-trimester exposure is a consideration but not an absolute contraindication." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "35499854", title: "Nintedanib in Progressive Pulmonary Fibrosis: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
  }
