      { text: "Chlamydia cervicitis (cannot distinguish clinically - NAAT confirms)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Chlamydia trachomatis causes clinically identical cervicitis with mucopurulent discharge and can also ascend to cause PID. The clinical presentations of gonorrhea and chlamydia cervicitis are indistinguishable; NAAT testing is required to identify the specific pathogen. A positive gonorrhea NAAT confirms gonococcal etiology." },
      { text: "Bacterial vaginosis with cervical discharge", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Bacterial vaginosis (BV) causes vaginal discharge (thin, grey, fishy odor) from altered vaginal flora, but does not cause mucopurulent cervical discharge, lower abdominal pain, or a positive gonorrhea NAAT. BV is a vaginal condition; gonococcal PID is a cervical/upper genital tract infection." },
      { text: "Trichomonas vaginalis infection with cervicitis", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Trichomonas vaginalis causes frothy yellow-green malodorous vaginal discharge and vulvovaginitis, and can cause mild cervicitis. However, it does not produce the mucopurulent cervical discharge or ascending PID characteristic of gonorrhea, and would not give a positive NAAT for N. gonorrhoeae." }
