      { text: "Ovarian failure from inflammatory damage to follicles", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "PID inflammation does not typically penetrate the ovarian cortex to damage follicles, as the tunica albuginea provides relative protection. Premature ovarian failure from PID is extremely rare. The dominant infertility mechanism is tubal damage rather than ovarian follicle destruction." },
      { text: "Cervical stenosis requiring surgical dilation", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Cervical stenosis (narrowing of the cervical canal) can complicate procedures like LEEP or severe endocervicitis but is not a recognized major complication of ascending PID. PID primarily damages the fallopian tubes and causes peritoneal adhesions rather than the cervix." },
      { text: "Endometrial cancer from chronic endometritis", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Endometrial cancer is not a complication of PID or chronic endometritis. Endometrial cancer is associated with estrogen excess (obesity, PCOS, HRT), not infection. PID's main long-term reproductive complications are tubal infertility, ectopic pregnancy, and chronic pelvic pain." }
