      { text: "Triad of migratory polyarthralgia, tenosynovitis, and dermatitis (pustular or vesiculopustular skin lesions) - or purulent monoarthritis", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "DGI presents in two phases: the bacteremic phase (migratory polyarthralgia, tenosynovitis, dermatitis with few-to-dozen pustular lesions on extremities) and the septic arthritis phase (purulent monoarthritis, usually knee, wrist, or ankle). Blood cultures are positive in <50%; synovial fluid culture is more sensitive in the joint phase." },
      { text: "Septicemic shock with meningococcemia-like purpura", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "N. meningitidis causes fulminant septicemia with large purpuric lesions from endothelial damage, petechiae, and disseminated intravascular coagulation—a life-threatening emergency. DGI (N. gonorrhoeae) causes scattered pustular/vesiculopustular lesions and polyarthralgia without the fulminant shock seen in meningococcemia." },
      { text: "Endocarditis with septic emboli as the primary manifestation", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Gonococcal endocarditis is a rare complication of DGI, not its primary manifestation. DGI most commonly causes the arthritis-dermatitis syndrome. Endocarditis occurs in <1-2% of DGI cases and should be suspected if blood cultures remain persistently positive or new murmurs develop despite appropriate antibiotic therapy." },
      { text: "Osteomyelitis of the long bones from hematogenous seeding", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Hematogenous osteomyelitis from N. gonorrhoeae is extremely rare; DGI preferentially affects synovial joints and tendon sheaths, not bone cortex. The arthritis-dermatitis syndrome of DGI involves synovial fluid and periarticular tenosynovium, not osteomyelitis of long bones as occurs with Staphylococcus aureus bacteremia." }
