      { text: "Topical erythromycin ointment (standard prophylaxis, not treatment for active infection)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Topical erythromycin 0.5% is the standard antibiotic eye prophylaxis applied at birth to prevent neonatal conjunctivitis (primarily chlamydial). It is ineffective as treatment for established gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum, which requires systemic ceftriaxone. This option correctly identifies the limitation but doesn't provide the treatment." },
      { text: "Topical ciprofloxacin drops are first-line for neonatal gonococcal conjunctivitis", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Topical antibiotic drops (including ciprofloxacin) are insufficient for gonococcal ophthalmia because Neisseria invades the corneal epithelium requiring systemic bactericidal levels. Additionally, quinolone resistance in N. gonorrhoeae makes topical ciprofloxacin unreliable. Systemic ceftriaxone is required." },
      { text: "No treatment needed as neonatal conjunctivitis is always self-limiting", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum is a medical emergency: without treatment, corneal ulceration progresses to perforation and permanent blindness within days. It is never self-limiting and requires urgent systemic ceftriaxone. Chemical conjunctivitis from silver nitrate is mild and self-limiting, but bacterial causes require prompt treatment." }
