      { text: "HIV - gonorrhea increases HIV transmission risk 3-5x by disrupting mucosal barriers and increasing local viral shedding", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Gonococcal urethritis/cervicitis increases HIV transmission through multiple mechanisms: mucosal inflammation and ulceration creating entry points for HIV, recruitment of CD4+ T cells and macrophages (HIV target cells) to the infection site, and increased HIV shedding in genital secretions. STI treatment reduces HIV transmission risk." },
      { text: "Herpes simplex - gonorrhea suppresses HSV immune control causing more frequent outbreaks", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Gonorrhea does not specifically suppress HSV-specific immunity to cause more frequent herpes outbreaks. HSV recurrence is primarily determined by host cellular immunity (CD8 T cells), stress, and systemic immunosuppression (HIV)—not by concurrent bacterial STIs like gonorrhea." },
      { text: "HPV - gonorrhea increases cervical cancer risk by promoting HPV integration", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "While inflammation from STIs may theoretically facilitate HPV persistence, gonorrhea does not specifically promote HPV genomic integration. HPV integration into host DNA leading to cervical cancer is driven by HPV biology (E6/E7 oncoproteins) and host immune factors, not by concurrent gonorrhea infection." },
      { text: "Syphilis - gonorrhea prevents treponeme colonization through competitive exclusion", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Gonorrhea does not prevent syphilis through competitive exclusion—co-infection with multiple STIs is common. Gonorrhea and syphilis can coexist, and STI co-infection epidemiology shows clustering of multiple infections in the same individuals with high-risk sexual behavior, not competitive exclusion." }
