      { text: "Embolism from Fabry cardiomyopathy causing atrial fibrillation", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Atrial fibrillation does occur in Fabry disease from cardiomyopathy and can cause cardioembolic stroke. However, cardioembolism is a secondary mechanism; the primary cerebrovascular pathology is direct Gb3-mediated vasculopathy in intracranial vessels causing lacunar infarcts and posterior circulation strokes independent of cardiac arrhythmia." },
      { text: "Vasculitis from immune complex deposition of Gb3 protein complexes", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Fabry cerebrovascular disease is not an inflammatory vasculitis—it is a storage vasculopathy from glycolipid accumulation in vessel walls. There are no immune complex deposits or inflammatory infiltrates in Fabry vessels. Anti-inflammatory treatments (steroids) are not effective for Fabry cerebrovascular disease." },
      { text: "Hyperviscosity from elevated plasma Gb3 causing sludging in cerebral microcirculation", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Plasma Gb3 levels are elevated in Fabry disease but not to the extent causing hyperviscosity syndrome. Hyperviscosity from plasma proteins occurs in Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia or multiple myeloma. Fabry cerebrovascular disease is from vessel wall glycolipid accumulation, not plasma hyperviscosity." }
