      { text: "Females have variable manifestations from lyonization (X-inactivation); many develop significant symptoms including neuropathy, cardiomyopathy, and renal disease requiring treatment", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Female Fabry carriers are heterozygous for GLA mutations. X-inactivation patterns vary between individuals and even between tissues. Skewed X-inactivation favoring the mutant allele in critical cell populations causes significant disease in many females. Current guidelines recommend treating symptomatic female Fabry patients with ERT." },
      { text: "Females are always asymptomatic carriers with no clinical manifestations", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Studies show that approximately 70% of female Fabry carriers develop at least one significant manifestation, and up to 50% have clinically meaningful cardiac involvement. The misconception that female carriers are uniformly asymptomatic led to historical underdiagnosis and undertreatment of affected women." },
      { text: "Females have more severe disease than hemizygous males", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Classical Fabry males are generally more severely affected than female carriers because all cells express the mutant allele in males (hemizygous), while females have a mixture of mutant-expressing and normal-expressing cells depending on X-inactivation. Females range from asymptomatic to significantly affected but usually less severely than classic males." },
      { text: "Female carriers develop only corneal deposits (cornea verticillata) without systemic involvement", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While corneal verticillata is common in female carriers (found in approximately 70-90%), it does not represent the extent of potential involvement. Female carriers can develop symptomatic neuropathic pain, progressive renal disease, cardiomyopathy with LV hypertrophy, and stroke—all warranting consideration for ERT." }
