      { text: "Pseudolymphoma reaction limited to blue ink", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Pseudolymphoma is a rare tattoo reaction that produces indurated nodules mimicking lymphoma histologically — it occurs most often with red or blue ink, but the eosinophilic infiltrate described here is more consistent with a simple Type IV hypersensitivity reaction rather than the dense lymphocytic infiltrate of pseudolymphoma." },
      { text: "Immediate IgE-mediated anaphylaxis to tattoo ink", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "IgE-mediated (Type I) hypersensitivity would cause urticaria, angioedema, or anaphylaxis within minutes of exposure — not a delayed onset reaction developing months after tattooing; the 3-month timeline and eosinophilic (rather than mast cell-dominated) biopsy exclude immediate hypersensitivity." },
      { text: "Superimposed bacterial infection of the tattoo site", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Bacterial infection presents acutely with purulent discharge, fever, and warmth within days of tattooing — not as isolated pruritic papules confined to one color 3 months later; the eosinophilic infiltrate on biopsy is an allergic finding, not consistent with bacterial infection." }
