      { text: "Azithromycin is preferred as it achieves better intracellular concentrations in infected endothelial cells", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Azithromycin achieves high intracellular concentrations and has been used as an alternative for mild rickettsial infections in pregnancy or doxycycline-allergic patients; however, clinical evidence for rickettsial infections consistently shows doxycycline superiority, making it the drug of choice rather than azithromycin." },
      { text: "Ciprofloxacin as rickettsiae are gram-negative organisms", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Rickettsiae have gram-negative outer membranes but this classification does not make them susceptible to fluoroquinolones; ciprofloxacin has limited activity against intracellular bacteria and is not recommended for rickettsial infections — the confusion arises from over-applying gram stain as a predictor of antibiotic coverage." },
      { text: "Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole as it is active against obligate intracellular bacteria", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "TMP-SMX is active against some obligate intracellular pathogens (Pneumocystis, certain Chlamydia species) but is notably not active against Rickettsia and is considered dangerous in rickettsial infections; paradoxically, TMP-SMX has been associated with worse outcomes in RMSF." }
