  {
    question: "Glucose loading is used for acute porphyria attacks because:",
    bloomLevel: "Understanding",
    competencyCode: "IM11.1",
    competencyText: "Understand mechanism of glucose-mediated ALAS1 suppression in porphyria",
    options: [
      { text: "Glucose induces insulin signaling that suppresses ALAS1 (rate-limiting heme synthesis enzyme) transcription by activating PGC-1alpha repression; this reduces flux through the blocked pathway decreasing toxic ALA/PBG accumulation", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "The glucose effect (also called the carbohydrate effect) was recognized before the molecular mechanism was elucidated; high glucose/insulin activates AKT which phosphorylates and inactivates PGC-1alpha, a transcriptional coactivator of ALAS1; this reduces ALAS1 expression and downstream ALA/PBG production — the same molecular pathway that explains why fasting triggers porphyria attacks (fasting activates PGC-1alpha, inducing ALAS1)." },
      { text: "Glucose directly chelates porphyrin precursors in the blood", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Glucose has no direct chemical chelation activity toward ALA, PBG, or porphyrins; the mechanism is purely regulatory through insulin-mediated ALAS1 transcriptional suppression, not through any direct chemical interaction between glucose and porphyrin precursors." },
      { text: "Glucose provides energy to compensate for mitochondrial dysfunction in porphyria", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "While ALA is neurotoxic in part through mitochondrial effects, the therapeutic mechanism of glucose loading is not to fuel compromised mitochondria but to suppress ALA production at the source through ALAS1 transcriptional regulation." },
      { text: "Glucose loading is a historical treatment with no mechanistic rationale", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Glucose loading has a well-established molecular mechanism through PGC-1alpha/ALAS1 suppression; it remains a first-line intervention for mild acute porphyria attacks where IV hemin is not yet available, with specific carbohydrate loading protocols (300-400g/day orally) defined in clinical guidelines." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "27982422", title: "Update review of the acute porphyrias.", publicationType: "Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "A variegate porphyria patient has a mild attack managed at home. Which monitoring is essential?",
    bloomLevel: "Application",
    competencyCode: "IM11.1",
    competencyText: "Apply monitoring parameters during acute porphyria attack",
    options: [
      { text: "Urine ALA and PBG to assess attack severity and treatment response; serum sodium (SIADH is common); blood pressure (hypertension); neurological status (motor weakness developing suggests severe attack needing IV hemin)", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "SIADH occurs during acute attacks from inappropriate ADH secretion driven by hypothalamic involvement — severe hyponatremia can cause seizures and worsen neurological status; hypertension reflects autonomic neuropathy; motor weakness progression (particularly ascending pattern) indicates neurological involvement requiring urgent IV hemin to prevent respiratory failure." },
      { text: "Only blood glucose monitoring during glucose loading therapy", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Blood glucose monitoring during glucose infusion is needed to avoid hyperglycemia, but it represents only one narrow component of attack monitoring; the key clinical parameters (serum sodium, neurological status, motor function) are more important for predicting attack severity and guiding escalation to IV hemin." },
      { text: "ALT monitoring as hepatic crisis is the primary concern", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "While porphyria can cause hepatic enzyme elevation, hepatic crisis is not the primary concern during acute attacks; the life-threatening complications are neurological (motor neuropathy, respiratory failure, seizures) and metabolic (SIADH-hyponatremia) — neurological monitoring takes priority over liver function tests." },
      { text: "Complete blood count monitoring for hemolytic anemia during attacks", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Acute porphyria attacks do not typically cause clinically significant hemolysis; hemolytic anemia is not a recognized complication of acute porphyria attacks; CBC monitoring would provide no clinically actionable information specific to porphyria attack management." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "27982422", title: "Update review of the acute porphyrias.", publicationType: "Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "A woman with variegate porphyria is prescribed oral contraceptives for another condition. What counseling should she receive?",
    bloomLevel: "Application",
    competencyCode: "IM11.1",
    competencyText: "Apply drug safety counseling for porphyria regarding hormonal contraceptives",
    options: [
      { text: "Progesterone-containing contraceptives can precipitate acute attacks by inducing ALAS1 activity; progestogen should be avoided or used cautiously; estrogen-only regimens and non-hormonal methods are safer options", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Progesterone and its synthetic analogues (progestogens) induce hepatic ALAS1 transcription, explaining why porphyria attacks cluster premenstrually (when progesterone peaks) and why progestogen-containing contraceptives are porphyrogenic; paradoxically, monthly LHRH analogues or continuous estrogen can actually prevent cyclical porphyria attacks." },
      { text: "All oral contraceptives are safe in all porphyria types", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Progestogen-containing contraceptives are specifically contraindicated or require careful risk-benefit assessment in acute porphyrias; the combined oral contraceptive pill containing progestogen can precipitate attacks in VP, AIP, and HCP patients with active disease — patient-specific counseling based on attack frequency and trigger patterns is required." },
      { text: "Estrogen specifically triggers porphyria attacks while progesterone is safe", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "This is the exact reverse of the pharmacological reality; progesterone (and synthetic progestogens) are the primary hormonal triggers for porphyria attacks, not estrogen; this misconception could lead to prescribing progestogen-only pills (which are specifically more porphyrogenic) while avoiding estrogen-only options that are actually safer." },
      { text: "Oral contraceptives are completely safe and the menstrual cycle suppression actually reduces cyclical porphyria attacks", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "While menstrual cycle suppression can be a goal in managing cyclical porphyria attacks, achieving this goal with progestogen-containing pills is counterproductive; LHRH analogues or continuous low-dose estrogen (not combined OCP) are the accepted approaches for suppressing hormonal cycling in severe cyclical porphyria." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "27982422", title: "Update review of the acute porphyrias.", publicationType: "Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "A patient with variegate porphyria develops progressive ascending motor neuropathy during an attack. This represents:",
    bloomLevel: "Analysis",
    competencyCode: "IM11.1",
    competencyText: "Analyze motor neuropathy as severe complication in acute porphyria attacks",
    options: [
      { text: "Potentially fatal bulbar and respiratory muscle weakness from ALA-mediated motor neuron toxicity - requires immediate IV hemin therapy to suppress ALA/PBG production and prevent respiratory failure", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "ALA (delta-aminolevulinic acid) directly inhibits GABA-A receptors and causes oxidative stress in motor neurons; ascending motor neuropathy in an acute porphyria attack is the most feared complication because it can progress to quadriplegia and respiratory arrest within hours; IV hemin (heme arginate) suppresses ALAS1 within hours, reducing toxic ALA/PBG levels." },
      { text: "A benign feature that always resolves spontaneously", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Progressive ascending motor weakness during an acute porphyria attack is a neurological emergency — it does not reliably resolve spontaneously and can progress to respiratory failure requiring mechanical ventilation; waiting for spontaneous resolution represents a dangerous clinical inaction that has led to preventable deaths." },
      { text: "Thiamine deficiency complicating the acute attack", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "While Wernicke encephalopathy can present during metabolic crises, the setting of an acute porphyria attack with progressive ascending motor weakness is much more parsimoniously explained by ALA-mediated motor neuron toxicity; thiamine deficiency would cause ocular abnormalities and confusion rather than ascending motor neuropathy." },
      { text: "Pre-existing peripheral neuropathy unrelated to the current porphyria attack", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "New progressive motor weakness developing during an acute porphyria attack must be attributed to the attack until proven otherwise; dismissing it as pre-existing would delay hemin therapy with potentially fatal consequences; chronic axonal neuropathy from repeated attacks is documented in porphyria, but new motor weakness during an active attack requires immediate treatment." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "27982422", title: "Update review of the acute porphyrias.", publicationType: "Review" }
  }
