    competencyText: "Recall Bartonella species causing culture-negative endocarditis",
    options: [
      { text: "Bartonella henselae and B. quintana are the most common causes of culture-negative endocarditis; serology (IgG titer >=1:800) and valve PCR are diagnostic", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Bartonella species account for approximately 3% of all endocarditis cases but represent the leading identifiable cause of 'blood culture-negative endocarditis' (BCNE) after exclusion of prior antibiotics and fastidious organisms. The Duke criteria require microbiological evidence: indirect immunofluorescence serology (IFA) showing B. henselae or B. quintana IgG titer ≥1:800 serves as a major criterion. Valve PCR from surgical specimens can identify the species when serology is equivocal. Affected patients almost always have structural valve disease." },
      { text: "Bartonella bacilliformis (Carrion disease - only in Andes region)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "B. bacilliformis does cause severe hematological disease but has not been reported as a cause of endocarditis outside of extremely rare reports. Its geographic restriction to Andean South America makes it an irrelevant consideration in non-endemic settings. The question describes a patient with aortic valve disease and cat exposure — the epidemiology points to B. henselae, the species responsible for the vast majority of Bartonella endocarditis cases globally." },
      { text: "Bartonella clarridgeiae (minor pathogen)", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "B. clarridgeiae is a minor Bartonella species found in cats that has been implicated in occasional CSD-like disease. It has minimal clinical significance as a pathogen and is essentially never reported as a cause of endocarditis. Including it as a differential for culture-negative endocarditis likely reflects theoretical knowledge that multiple Bartonella species exist, but clinically meaningful Bartonella endocarditis is overwhelmingly caused by B. henselae and B. quintana." },
      { text: "All Bartonella species equally cause endocarditis without predilection", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "The epidemiology of Bartonella endocarditis is clearly not uniform across species. B. henselae and B. quintana together account for >95% of Bartonella endocarditis cases. B. bacilliformis endocarditis is essentially unreported. Minor species (clarridgeiae, elizabethae) contribute trivially. Serology testing specifically targets B. henselae and B. quintana for this reason. Stating all species equally cause endocarditis misrepresents the clinical evidence base and would lead to inappropriate testing strategies." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "23602630", title: "Treatment outcomes of human bartonellosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
