  {
    question: "Carrion disease (Oroya fever + Verruga peruana) is caused by Bartonella bacilliformis. Which vector transmits it?",
    bloomLevel: "Recall",
    competencyCode: "IM7.9",
    competencyText: "Recall vector for Bartonella bacilliformis",
    options: [
      { text: "Phlebotomus (Lutzomyia verrucarum) sandfly - endemic only in Andean valleys of Peru, Ecuador, and Colombia at specific altitude ranges", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Bartonella bacilliformis is transmitted exclusively by the sandfly Lutzomyia verrucarum (formerly classified as Phlebotomus), which thrives at specific altitudes (800-3200m) in the inter-Andean valleys. The geographic restriction is absolute: Carrion disease has never been reported outside this Andean belt. The disease is named after Daniel Carrion, a Peruvian medical student who died in 1885 after self-inoculating with Verruga peruana material to prove the diseases were caused by the same pathogen." },
      { text: "Cat scratch or bite (that transmits B. henselae)", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "The confusion between Bartonella species and their vectors is a common knowledge gap. B. henselae (CSD) uses cats as reservoir hosts and cat fleas (Ctenocephalides felis) as vectors between cats — transmitted to humans via cat scratches contaminated with flea feces. B. bacilliformis uses no feline host and no flea vector; it is exclusively sandfly-borne in Andean valleys. Both are Bartonella species, but their ecology, geography, and vectors are entirely different." },
      { text: "Body louse (that transmits B. quintana/trench fever)", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Body lice (Pediculus humanus corporis) transmit B. quintana causing trench fever — another Bartonella species with a different vector from both B. henselae and B. bacilliformis. With three major Bartonella species having three different vectors (cat flea, body louse, sandfly), confusion about which vector belongs to which species is understandable. The geographic clue (Andean endemic) points to B. bacilliformis and its sandfly vector specifically." },
      { text: "Ixodes tick (that transmits Lyme disease)", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Ixodes ticks transmit Borrelia burgdorferi (Lyme disease), Babesia microti, Anaplasma phagocytophilum, and Ehrlichia, but not any Bartonella species. Ticks as vectors for Bartonella has been theorized but not established for the main clinical Bartonella pathogens. Confusing tick-borne spirochetal disease with sandfly-borne Bartonella bacilliformis reflects general 'vector-borne disease' pattern-matching rather than specific knowledge of individual pathogen-vector relationships." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "23602630", title: "Treatment outcomes of human bartonellosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "The acute phase of Carrion disease (Oroya fever) causes life-threatening:",
    bloomLevel: "Recall",
    competencyCode: "IM7.9",
    competencyText: "Recall acute hemolytic phase of Bartonella bacilliformis infection",
    options: [
      { text: "Acute hemolytic anemia - B. bacilliformis parasitizes RBCs causing massive hemolysis with up to 80% RBC loss; case fatality rate 40-90% without treatment", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Bartonella bacilliformis invades erythrocytes (unlike other Bartonella species) by attaching to spectrin and deforming the RBC cytoskeleton, leading to massive phagocytosis of parasitized cells by the reticuloendothelial system. Oroya fever represents one of the most severe acute hemolytic anemias known — patients can lose 80% of circulating RBCs within 2-3 weeks, presenting with severe normocytic anemia, jaundice, and hepatosplenomegaly. Chloramphenicol was historically curative; modern treatment uses ciprofloxacin or amoxicillin with excellent outcomes if initiated early." },
      { text: "Hepatic failure from direct hepatocyte invasion", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Hepatic involvement (hepatomegaly, jaundice from hemolysis) is prominent in Oroya fever, which might suggest hepatocyte invasion. However, the jaundice is hemolytic (indirect hyperbilirubinemia from massive RBC destruction) rather than hepatocellular. B. bacilliformis targets RBCs, not hepatocytes. Direct hepatocyte invasion and liver failure is not the mechanism — the liver enlargement reflects reticuloendothelial hyperplasia from phagocytosing destroyed RBCs and systemic bacteremia." },
      { text: "Disseminated intravascular coagulation from Bartonella endotoxin", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "DIC from bacterial endotoxin is characteristic of gram-negative sepsis with lipopolysaccharide. Bartonella bacilliformis is a gram-negative intracellular bacterium but its primary virulence is through direct RBC parasitism rather than endotoxin-mediated coagulation cascade activation. DIC can complicate severe Oroya fever secondarily from the massive hemolysis and tissue hypoperfusion, but it is not the primary mechanism of life-threatening disease — the acute hemolytic anemia itself is the primary cause of death." },
      { text: "Cardiac arrhythmia from cardiac Bartonella seeding", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Cardiac seeding by Bartonella in the acute phase of Carrion disease is not a recognized pathological mechanism. B. quintana (not bacilliformis) causes endocarditis through a different intracellular parasitism of endothelial cells. In Oroya fever, death occurs from severe hemolytic anemia causing cardiovascular collapse from profound anemia (hemoglobin may fall to 2-3 g/dL) — high-output cardiac failure from anemia, not direct Bartonella cardiac seeding or arrhythmia." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "23602630", title: "Treatment outcomes of human bartonellosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "The skin lesions of Verruga peruana (chronic phase Carrion disease) histologically resemble:",
    bloomLevel: "Analysis",
    competencyCode: "PA4.1",
    competencyText: "Analyze histological similarity between Verruga peruana and bacillary angiomatosis",
    options: [
      { text: "Bacillary angiomatosis - both show vascular proliferation with Bartonella; distinguish by Warthin-Starry stain showing the bacteria and geographic/immunological context", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Verruga peruana (chronic phase Carrion disease) and bacillary angiomatosis share nearly identical histopathology: lobular vascular proliferation with plump endothelial cells and mixed inflammatory infiltrate. Both contain clusters of Bartonella organisms visualized by Warthin-Starry silver stain. The clinical distinction relies on immunological status (immunocompetent Andean patient with Verruga vs. profoundly immunocompromised patient with BA) and geographic context (Andean endemic region vs. worldwide HIV disease). PCR and serology confirm the specific Bartonella species." },
      { text: "Kaposi sarcoma - identical histology without bacterial etiology", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Kaposi sarcoma (KS) and BA both cause purple vascular skin lesions in HIV patients, and clinical distinction is extremely challenging without biopsy. Histologically, however, KS shows characteristic slit-like vascular spaces lined by spindle cells with erythrocyte extravasation — different from the lobular capillary proliferation of BA. Warthin-Starry stain for bacteria is negative in KS, and KS is caused by HHV-8 (human herpesvirus 8), not Bartonella. Distinguishing them matters enormously because BA is curable with antibiotics while KS requires different management." },
      { text: "Pyogenic granuloma - bland vascular proliferation without bacteria", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Pyogenic granuloma is a benign vascular lobular capillary hemangioma that shares architectural features with Verruga peruana and BA. However, pyogenic granuloma has no bacterial etiology (Warthin-Starry stain negative), no Bartonella organisms, and occurs in immunocompetent patients without travel to Andean regions or HIV. The capillary lobule pattern is shared across all three, but the presence of Bartonella organisms visible on silver stain specifically identifies both Verruga and BA." },
      { text: "Leishmania skin lesion - shows intracellular amastigotes", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "Cutaneous leishmaniasis (caused by Leishmania species transmitted by Phlebotomus sandflies) does share geographic overlap with Carrion disease in South America and presents with skin ulcers in the same endemic regions. However, leishmaniasis shows granulomatous inflammation with intracellular amastigotes (Leishman-Donovan bodies) in macrophages — completely different histology from the vascular proliferative lesions of Verruga peruana. Giemsa or H&E stain shows amastigotes in macrophages, not angiomatous endothelial proliferation." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "23602630", title: "Treatment outcomes of human bartonellosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
  },
  {
    question: "An HIV patient is found to have Bartonella quintana bacteremia with splenomegaly. CD4 is 45. What is the management?",
    bloomLevel: "Application",
    competencyCode: "IM7.9",
    competencyText: "Apply management of severe Bartonella infection in HIV",
    options: [
      { text: "Doxycycline plus rifampicin for 4-6 months for bacteremia/disseminated disease; optimize ART to restore immune function; relapse prevention requires continued suppressive therapy in profoundly immunocompromised patients", type: "correct", distanceScore: 0, distanceLabel: "Correct", explanation: "Disseminated Bartonella quintana bacteremia with splenomegaly in an HIV patient with CD4 45 represents severe immunocompromised bartonellosis requiring prolonged combination therapy. Doxycycline provides intracellular activity; rifampicin adds bactericidal coverage against intracellular Bartonella and reduces emergence of resistance. Treatment duration of 4-6 months prevents relapse. With CD4 45, immune reconstitution through ART is essential — as CD4 rises above 200, maintenance therapy can eventually be discontinued safely." },
      { text: "Single-course azithromycin for HIV-associated Bartonella bacteremia", type: "similar_wrong", distanceScore: 1, distanceLabel: "Close but wrong", explanation: "Short-course azithromycin (5 days) is appropriate for uncomplicated CSD in immunocompetent patients but is grossly inadequate for bacteremia in severely immunocompromised patients. With CD4 45, the patient lacks the T-cell immunity needed to clear residual intracellular bacteria after antibiotics are stopped. Short-course treatment in this context leads to bacteremia relapse within weeks, progressive dissemination, and risk of endocarditis or bacillary peliosis hepatis (hepatic BA)." },
      { text: "No antibiotic needed until CD4 rises above 200 with ART", type: "misconception", distanceScore: 2, distanceLabel: "Common misconception", explanation: "Active bacteremia with systemic symptoms (splenomegaly, fever) in an immunocompromised patient cannot be managed expectantly while awaiting immune reconstitution from ART. ART takes weeks to months to raise CD4 counts sufficiently, during which untreated Bartonella bacteremia can progress to endocarditis, peliosis hepatis, or death. Simultaneous antibiotic therapy and ART initiation is required. The misconception may reflect overcautious thinking about Jarisch-Herxheimer reactions or IRIS, which do not apply here." },
      { text: "IV gentamicin for bacteremia followed by oral step-down", type: "wildly_wrong", distanceScore: 3, distanceLabel: "Way off", explanation: "IV gentamicin has no established role in uncomplicated Bartonella bacteremia. Gentamicin has been combined with doxycycline specifically for Bartonella endocarditis (synergistic bactericidal activity on valve vegetations), but bacteremia without endocarditis does not require aminoglycoside therapy. Gentamicin's nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity make it inappropriate for months-long maintenance therapy in HIV patients who already have impaired renal clearance risks from multiple medications." }
    ],
    pubmedSource: { pmid: "23602630", title: "Treatment outcomes of human bartonellosis: a systematic review and meta-analysis.", publicationType: "Systematic Review" }
  }
